			<h1>Ecology &amp; Environment</h1>
			<div class="col-sm-8" id="post-list">
				    <article class="card short list-item">
        <div class="card-photo ">
    <a tabindex="-1" aria-hidden="true" role="presentation" href="/https://news.stanford.edu/2018/08/02/fishing-bans-protect-fish-dont-harm-fishing-communities/"><img class="attachment-post-thumbnail size-post-thumbnail wp-post-image" alt="Fishing vessels like this one were tracked during a short-lived trawling moratorium in the Adriatic Sea as part of a Stanford study." srcset="https://news-media.stanford.edu/wp-content/uploads/2019/04/26101415/adriatic1-200x200.jpg 200w, https://news-media.stanford.edu/wp-content/uploads/2019/04/26101415/adriatic1-100x100.jpg 100w" sizes="(max-width: 200px) 100vw, 200px" src="/https://news-media.stanford.edu/wp-content/uploads/2019/04/26101415/adriatic1-200x200.jpg"></a>
  </div>  <div class="card-content">
    <div class="meta"><time datetime="2018-08-02T00:01:00+00:00">August 2, 2018</time></div>
    <h3><a href="/https://news.stanford.edu/2018/08/02/fishing-bans-protect-fish-dont-harm-fishing-communities/">Fishing bans protect fish and don’t harm fishing communities</a></h3>
    <p class="teaser">Fishers who complied with a moratorium in the Adriatic Sea maintained catch levels by fishing in other areas. The findings help justify extending regional protection and provide insight for ocean management elsewhere.</p>
  </div>    </article>
    <article class="card short list-item">
        <div class="card-photo ">
    <a tabindex="-1" aria-hidden="true" role="presentation" href="/https://news.stanford.edu/2018/07/24/border-wall-threatens-biodiversity/"><img class="attachment-post-thumbnail size-post-thumbnail wp-post-image" alt="A family of javelinas encounters the wall on the U.S.-Mexico border near the San Pedro River in southeastern Arizona." srcset="https://news-media.stanford.edu/wp-content/uploads/2018/07/20112734/border_wall1-200x200.jpg 200w, https://news-media.stanford.edu/wp-content/uploads/2018/07/20112734/border_wall1-100x100.jpg 100w" sizes="(max-width: 200px) 100vw, 200px" src="/https://news-media.stanford.edu/wp-content/uploads/2018/07/20112734/border_wall1-200x200.jpg"></a>
  </div>  <div class="card-content">
    <div class="meta"><time datetime="2018-07-24T09:00:33+00:00">July 24, 2018</time></div>
    <h3><a href="/https://news.stanford.edu/2018/07/24/border-wall-threatens-biodiversity/">Border wall threatens biodiversity</a></h3>
    <p class="teaser">Federal plans to complete a continuous wall along the U.S.-Mexico boundary would threaten the existence of numerous plant and animal species, Stanford researchers say. Paul Ehrlich and Rodolfo Dirzo look at the region’s unique natural ecosystems, and what they have to lose.</p>
  </div>    </article>
    <article class="card short list-item">
        <div class="card-photo ">
    <a tabindex="-1" aria-hidden="true" role="presentation" href="/https://news.stanford.edu/2018/07/23/widespread-groundwater-contamination-risk-chromium/"><img class="attachment-post-thumbnail size-post-thumbnail wp-post-image" alt="Water gushes from a pipe into a farm irrigation canal in Central California." srcset="https://news-media.stanford.edu/wp-content/uploads/2018/07/20145138/chromium-200x200.jpg 200w, https://news-media.stanford.edu/wp-content/uploads/2018/07/20145138/chromium-100x100.jpg 100w" sizes="(max-width: 200px) 100vw, 200px" src="/https://news-media.stanford.edu/wp-content/uploads/2018/07/20145138/chromium-200x200.jpg"></a>
  </div>  <div class="card-content">
    <div class="meta"><time datetime="2018-07-23T00:01:42+00:00">July 23, 2018</time></div>
    <h3><a href="/https://news.stanford.edu/2018/07/23/widespread-groundwater-contamination-risk-chromium/">Widespread groundwater contamination risk from chromium</a></h3>
    <p class="teaser">Natural sources of the toxic form of chromium appear in wells that provide drinking water to a large population in California, offering a new perspective on California’s groundwater management challenges.</p>
  </div>    </article>
    <article class="card short list-item">
        <div class="card-photo ">
    <a tabindex="-1" aria-hidden="true" role="presentation" href="/https://news.stanford.edu/2018/07/16/poll-shows-consensus-climate-policy-remains-strong/"><img class="attachment-post-thumbnail size-post-thumbnail wp-post-image" alt="smoke coming from an oil refinery in the U.S." srcset="https://news-media.stanford.edu/wp-content/uploads/2018/07/13123432/attitudes-200x200.jpg 200w, https://news-media.stanford.edu/wp-content/uploads/2018/07/13123432/attitudes-100x100.jpg 100w" sizes="(max-width: 200px) 100vw, 200px" src="/https://news-media.stanford.edu/wp-content/uploads/2018/07/13123432/attitudes-200x200.jpg"></a>
  </div>  <div class="card-content">
    <div class="meta"><time datetime="2018-07-16T00:01:18+00:00">July 16, 2018</time></div>
    <h3><a href="/https://news.stanford.edu/2018/07/16/poll-shows-consensus-climate-policy-remains-strong/">Poll shows consensus for climate policy remains strong</a></h3>
    <p class="teaser">A new study shows that Americans overwhelmingly want a reduction in global warming and support renewable energy development. But according to the data, Americans don’t realize how many people share their beliefs.</p>
  </div>    </article>
    <article class="card short list-item">
        <div class="card-photo ">
    <a tabindex="-1" aria-hidden="true" role="presentation" href="/https://medium.com/freeman-spogli-institute-for-international-studies/nuclear-waste-costs-americans-billions-every-year-3197935352ff"><img class="attachment-post-thumbnail size-post-thumbnail wp-post-image" alt="Radioactive waste" srcset="https://news-media.stanford.edu/wp-content/uploads/2018/07/09150348/nukewaste-200x200.jpg 200w, https://news-media.stanford.edu/wp-content/uploads/2018/07/09150348/nukewaste-100x100.jpg 100w" sizes="(max-width: 200px) 100vw, 200px" src="/https://news-media.stanford.edu/wp-content/uploads/2018/07/09150348/nukewaste-200x200.jpg"></a>
  </div>  <div class="card-content">
    <div class="meta">Freeman Spogli Institute for International Studies — <time datetime="2018-07-09T15:04:14+00:00">July 9, 2018</time></div>
    <h3><a href="/https://medium.com/freeman-spogli-institute-for-international-studies/nuclear-waste-costs-americans-billions-every-year-3197935352ff">Nuclear waste costs Americans billions every year</a></h3>
    <p class="teaser">Since the Manhattan Project officially began in 1942, the United States has faced ever-increasing stores of nuclear waste.</p>
  </div>    </article>
    <article class="card short list-item">
        <div class="card-photo ">
    <a tabindex="-1" aria-hidden="true" role="presentation" href="/https://news.stanford.edu/2018/07/02/learning-through-sound/"><img class="attachment-post-thumbnail size-post-thumbnail wp-post-image" alt="" srcset="https://news-media.stanford.edu/wp-content/uploads/2018/07/02134301/listening_featured_image-200x200.jpg 200w, https://news-media.stanford.edu/wp-content/uploads/2018/07/02134301/listening_featured_image-100x100.jpg 100w" sizes="(max-width: 200px) 100vw, 200px" src="/https://news-media.stanford.edu/wp-content/uploads/2018/07/02134301/listening_featured_image-200x200.jpg"></a>
  </div>  <div class="card-content">
    <div class="meta"><time datetime="2018-07-02T14:00:56+00:00">July 2, 2018</time></div>
    <h3><a href="/https://news.stanford.edu/2018/07/02/learning-through-sound/">Learning through sound</a></h3>
    <p class="teaser">The audible world contains vast amounts of information about the world around us. Scholars from across Stanford are exploring this invisible landscape&nbsp;as a research tool and as a way of understanding each other.</p>
  </div>    </article>
    <article class="card short list-item">
        <div class="card-photo ">
    <a tabindex="-1" aria-hidden="true" role="presentation" href="/https://news.stanford.edu/2018/06/28/new-national-ocean-policy-implications-oceans-business/"><img class="attachment-post-thumbnail size-post-thumbnail wp-post-image" alt="A recreational sailboat in front of the Statue of Liberty, with signs of industry in the background." srcset="https://news-media.stanford.edu/wp-content/uploads/2018/06/28152520/ocean_policy-200x200.jpg 200w, https://news-media.stanford.edu/wp-content/uploads/2018/06/28152520/ocean_policy-100x100.jpg 100w" sizes="(max-width: 200px) 100vw, 200px" src="/https://news-media.stanford.edu/wp-content/uploads/2018/06/28152520/ocean_policy-200x200.jpg"></a>
  </div>  <div class="card-content">
    <div class="meta"><time datetime="2018-06-28T16:13:31+00:00">June 28, 2018</time></div>
    <h3><a href="/https://news.stanford.edu/2018/06/28/new-national-ocean-policy-implications-oceans-business/">New National Ocean Policy: Implications for oceans and business</a></h3>
    <p class="teaser">The federal government rescinded the Obama-era National Ocean Policy and replaced it with new policies intended to promote jobs and national security. Stanford experts examine potential unintended implications.</p>
  </div>    </article>
    <article class="card short list-item">
        <div class="card-photo ">
    <a tabindex="-1" aria-hidden="true" role="presentation" href="/https://news.stanford.edu/2018/06/27/air-pollution-major-cause-infant-deaths-sub-saharan-africa/"><img class="attachment-post-thumbnail size-post-thumbnail wp-post-image" alt="view of polluted air in a city in Cameroon" srcset="https://news-media.stanford.edu/wp-content/uploads/2018/06/21161910/infantmortality-200x200.jpg 200w, https://news-media.stanford.edu/wp-content/uploads/2018/06/21161910/infantmortality-100x100.jpg 100w" sizes="(max-width: 200px) 100vw, 200px" src="/https://news-media.stanford.edu/wp-content/uploads/2018/06/21161910/infantmortality-200x200.jpg"></a>
  </div>  <div class="card-content">
    <div class="meta"><time datetime="2018-06-27T10:00:43+00:00">June 27, 2018</time></div>
    <h3><a href="/https://news.stanford.edu/2018/06/27/air-pollution-major-cause-infant-deaths-sub-saharan-africa/">Air pollution a major cause of infant deaths in sub-Saharan Africa</a></h3>
    <p class="teaser">Satellite measurements of air quality across sub-Saharan Africa revealed small improvements in air quality could be one of the most effective interventions to curb infant mortality rates.</p>
  </div>    </article>
    <article class="card short list-item">
        <div class="card-photo ">
    <a tabindex="-1" aria-hidden="true" role="presentation" href="/https://earth.stanford.edu/news/warmer-climate-will-dramatically-increase-volatility-global-corn-crops"><img class="attachment-post-thumbnail size-post-thumbnail wp-post-image" alt="Cornfield" srcset="https://news-media.stanford.edu/wp-content/uploads/2018/06/12105236/GettyImages-825722908-200x200.jpg 200w, https://news-media.stanford.edu/wp-content/uploads/2018/06/12105236/GettyImages-825722908-100x100.jpg 100w" sizes="(max-width: 200px) 100vw, 200px" src="/https://news-media.stanford.edu/wp-content/uploads/2018/06/12105236/GettyImages-825722908-200x200.jpg"></a>
  </div>  <div class="card-content">
    <div class="meta">Stanford School of Earth, Energy &amp; Environmental Sciences — <time datetime="2018-06-12T10:53:34+00:00">June 12, 2018</time></div>
    <h3><a href="/https://earth.stanford.edu/news/warmer-climate-will-dramatically-increase-volatility-global-corn-crops">Warmer climate will dramatically increase global corn crop volatility</a></h3>
    <p class="teaser">A new study co-authored by a Stanford Earth researcher looks at what climate change will mean for global yields of corn, or maize, the most widely grown crop in the world.</p>
  </div>    </article>
    <article class="card short list-item">
        <div class="card-photo ">
    <a tabindex="-1" aria-hidden="true" role="presentation" href="/https://news.stanford.edu/2018/06/11/nectar-research-sheds-light-ecological-theory/"><img class="attachment-post-thumbnail size-post-thumbnail wp-post-image" alt="Cells of Metschnikowia gruessii, one of the four species of nectar-inhabiting yeasts that were used by the Fukami Lab to study how species coexist." srcset="https://news-media.stanford.edu/wp-content/uploads/2018/06/08165006/Fluctutation1-200x200.jpg 200w, https://news-media.stanford.edu/wp-content/uploads/2018/06/08165006/Fluctutation1-100x100.jpg 100w" sizes="(max-width: 200px) 100vw, 200px" src="/https://news-media.stanford.edu/wp-content/uploads/2018/06/08165006/Fluctutation1-200x200.jpg"></a>
  </div>  <div class="card-content">
    <div class="meta"><time datetime="2018-06-11T12:00:30+00:00">June 11, 2018</time></div>
    <h3><a href="/https://news.stanford.edu/2018/06/11/nectar-research-sheds-light-ecological-theory/">Nectar research sheds light on ecological theory</a></h3>
    <p class="teaser">Different species almost always coexist, but how that works is complicated. Now, Stanford researchers have teased apart competing theories of how species live together.</p>
  </div>    </article>
